-- Overseas Investors Pour 33 Billion Rupees in India, Most in Seven Weeks
-- B y   P a r e s h   J a t a k i a
-- 2010-09-22T09:54:48Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-09-22/overseas-investors-pour-33-billion-rupees-in-india-most-in-seven-weeks.html
Overseas  funds  bought a net  33.1
billion rupees  ($724.4 million) of Indian equities yesterday,
the most in seven weeks, according to the market regulator.  Investors purchased 64.3 billion rupees of shares and sold
31.2 billion rupees, the Securities and Exchange Board of India
said  today . The net inflow is the most since July 29.  Global funds have placed 787 billion rupees in stocks this
year, including 212 billion rupees in the primary markets, the
data show. The flows have helped the benchmark Sensitive index
rise above 20,000 for the first time since January 2008 and the
pushed the rupee up 4.8 percent from an eight-month low in May.  Overseas  investors  have invested 3.926 trillion rupees in
stocks and 758.2 billion rupees in bonds since they were allowed
into the country in 1993. Flows reached a record 834.2 billion
rupees in 2009, sparking the biggest rally in 18 years. They
pulled out a record 530 billion rupees from stocks in 2008,
setting off the worst annual slump.  The regulator provides data on shares bought and sold by
large investors, including trades in the primary and secondary
markets, with a delay of at least a day.  To contact the reporter on this story:
